Question: What improvements would you like to see in these cultural funding programs?

Response ID: resp_1408
Response Text: I believe funding was pulled from groups that represent important aspects of music and art because they appeared on the surface to be not diverse enough. But the justification for pulling that funding felt barely researched, and those organizations that represent diverse KINDS of art and a broad scope of TIME PERIODS were left to fend for themselves. Ensemble VIII literally died. That is a loss for audiences who enjoyed listening to early music and artists who relied on that work. The closest cultural centers to us that do any early music at all are Houston and outside of Texas. Large organizations that used to receive more funding have cut their season activity because they couldn't pay artists. Those funding cuts made a lasting impact on artists in Austin that relied on regular work. It was so poorly thought through in the name of supporting DEI, but I don't know that those funding decisions actually did what ACME hoped it would do. It left a wide variety of artists, of varying gender identities, races, religions, etc., with less work, less money, and fewer opportunities. Cultural fixtures in Austin that actually do support DEI suffered, and so did the reputation of ACME. I think a wider lense is necessary when making funding decisions, with more informed members making those decisions about the art on the table. Some of the feedback and questions that came back to orgs when they didn't receive funding were clearly ill-informed and sometimes downright embarrassing.

